Phase 7 #9 — user picks from queued candidates (Socket.IO realtime foundation live since Phase 7 #8e — instrumentation.ts hook + auth middleware + org-scoped channels + 60s revalidation loop; JWT carries organizationSlug; middleware enforces URL↔session match; coverage gate live since Phase 7 #5; per-user 24h reset cap live since Phase 7 #6; TDD mandatory per Rule 25)

Phase 7 #8 (e) Socket.IO realtime foundation shipped on 2026-05-16:
- (e)-1 [SHA `dd57c9c`] — bootstrap + auth middleware. Next.js 15 instrumentation.ts hook spawns Socket.IO HTTP server on SOCKET_PORT (43515 dev = base+13), separate from APP_PORT. Dynamic imports keep instrumentation Edge-bundle-safe. server/socket/server.ts: createSocketServer factory with CORS to NEXT_PUBLIC_APP_URL + credentials:true (cross-port = cross-origin for the Auth.js cookie); installs socketAuthMiddleware on io.use(). server/socket/auth.ts: verifySocketAuth({cookieHeader, isProduction}) pure function parses Auth.js v5 cookie (authjs.session-token dev / __Secure-authjs.session-token prod) and decodes with cookie name as JWE salt — Auth.js v5 derives the AEAD key from secret + cookie-name, so wrong salt returns null even with right secret. Narrows decoded JWT mirroring auth.config.ts session callback; rejects on missing organizationSlug/Id/role/securityVersion. NEW auth.test.ts with 13 cases. RED→GREEN proven inline.
- (e)-2 [SHA `c399b43`] — org channels + 60s revalidation. server/socket/channels.ts: orgChannelName/platformChannelName formatters per DECISIONS_LOG.md:173 (${tenantId}:${eventType}). joinOrgChannel(socket, eventType) takes NO orgId parameter so cross-org subscription is API-impossible — the helper always reads session.organizationId, so a malicious client cannot coerce subscription to another org through the API surface. joinPlatformChannel requires session.isSuperAdmin === true. server/socket/revalidation.ts: revalidateConnectedSockets walks io.fetchSockets(), dedupes userIds, single platformPrisma.user.findMany including organization.suspended_at, disconnects sockets failing any of 4 staleness conditions; emits "session:invalidated" before disconnect. startSessionRevalidationLoop is the setInterval wrapper with .unref(). NEW channels.test.ts (10) + revalidation.test.ts (9). instrumentation.ts wires the cleanup.
- (e)-3 — governance batch only (this update). New DECISIONS_LOG entry "Realtime Hosting Topology (Phase 7 #8e)" locks option B over A (custom server) or C (separate compose service).
- Tier 3 decomposition: 12 files (8 new + 4 modified), score 49 > 40 threshold → mandatory 3-session split per memory-governance §1. All 3 sub-sessions Opus self-executed per Phase 7 #7c's [[sonnet-thrash-sessionstart-hooks]] precedent. ~90K total Opus context, well under 100K ceiling.
- Tests: 42 → 75 (+33). trpc/routers/auth.ts per-file gate intact at 100/80.95/100/100. Globals: 21.37→29.43 stmts / 16.1→25.06 branches.
- User-confirmed decisions: (1) hosting topology = option B (instrumentation + separate port); (2) decomposition = 2 sub-sessions + governance.
- 3 new lessons: (🟤) Auth.js v5 JWE cookie-name-as-salt; (🟤) cross-org subscription guard via API-surface design; (🟤) Next.js 15 instrumentation.ts hosting topology decision.

----------------------------------------------------------------------
Candidates for Phase 7 #9 (any order, user picks):
----------------------------------------------------------------------

(j) Resolve nodemailer HIGH CVE (GHSA-rcmh-qjqh-p98v)   [security — small + safe, RECOMMENDED NEXT]
    addressparser DoS via recursive calls affects <=7.0.10; we run 6.9.16 pinned for
    Auth.js v5 peer compat. Three documented paths in lessons.md:
      (a) wait for @auth to widen its nodemailer peer range — cleanest, no code changes
      (b) replace nodemailer with a different transport library — touches email.ts + callsites
      (c) document mitigation (server-stamped addresses only, attacker cannot reach the
          vulnerable parser through the password-reset flow) + add `audit-level=critical`
          to .npmrc per phases.md decision tree step 3
    Path (c) is the realistic short-term option; (a) is the long-term hope; (b) is
    last-resort. Single-commit ticket — Tier 1. Pre-existing on main since before Phase 7 #5.
    Closes the only remaining `pnpm audit` failure on main.

(presence) Real-time presence engine (NEW — unblocked by #8e)
    Now ready to consume the Socket.IO foundation. Scope: emit on socket.connect /
    socket.disconnect to broadcast online/offline state to org subscribers via
    joinOrgChannel(socket, "presence"). Pairs with Speed Dial Board UI
    (PRODUCT.md:27 — "real-time online/offline presence indicator").
    Department-binding presence (device_binding_token on Department model) is the
    natural extension. Tier 2-3. RED-GREEN test pattern: assert emitToOrg called
    with correct room name + payload on socket.io connect/disconnect events.

(socket-client) Client-side socket.io-client provider hook (NEW — unblocked by #8e)
    Small Tier 1 ticket. Build the React provider that connects to NEXT_PUBLIC_SOCKET_URL
    with `credentials: include` (so the Auth.js cookie flows), exposes a useSocket() hook
    returning a typed socket reference, and surfaces "session:invalidated" disconnect
    events as a forced re-auth UX (redirect to /login). Pairs naturally with (presence)
    since the first consumer needs a client socket; can ship together if scope allows.

(i) Periodic cleanup of expired/consumed password_reset_tokens
    A BullMQ scheduled job to DELETE consumed tokens > 30 days old and unconsumed
    expired tokens > 7 days. Keeps the table from growing unboundedly.
    Pairs naturally with #6: the cap-met silent-skip and the cleanup job
    together close the token-table lifecycle. The count query introduced in #6
    stays fast forever if the cleanup runs daily. Tier 2 (BullMQ worker + scheduler
    + tests + deploy config).

(d) join/[token] tRPC                          [needs LiveKit ⏳ for full integration]
    Unit tests OK against mocked LiveKit token mint; integration deferred until LIVEKIT_API_KEY filled.
    Existing getJoinToken in meetingsRouter has 0 test coverage — could pair with this if scope allows.

(f) Root landing page                          [verify scope first]
    Current /page.tsx is 11 lines — check PRODUCT.md for what's expected. Likely Tier 1.

----------------------------------------------------------------------
Rule 25 reminder for ALL of the above:
  → Write failing test FIRST (RED), then implementation (GREEN), then refactor.
  → Test patterns:
      [[trpc-test-pattern]] (Phase 7 #2)
      [[meetings-protected-route-test]] (Phase 7 #3)
      [[trpc-test-with-env-mock]] (Phase 7 #4)
      [[direct-callback-test-pattern]] (Phase 7 #7c-1 — exercises authConfig.callbacks directly)
      [[pure-helper-extraction-pattern]] (Phase 7 #7c-2 / #8e — extract Edge-incompatible code into separate file for Node test runner)
      [[socket-auth-test-pattern]] (Phase 7 #8e-1 — mock next-auth/jwt decode + assert decode receives correct salt)
      [[socket-revalidation-test-pattern]] (Phase 7 #8e-2 — mock io.fetchSockets + prisma.user.findMany; assert disconnect/emit per stale-session branch)
  → For forms: reuse the [[shadcn-form-primitive]] pattern from Phase 7 #3.
  → For shared schemas: `<Entity>CreateClientInputSchema` for client-facing input, `<Entity>CreateInputSchema` for admin/internal projection.
  → For new env vars consumed by routers: add `vi.mock("@/env", ...)` to the test file.
  → For new JWT fields: wire BOTH session callbacks (auth.config.ts Edge-safe AND auth.ts DB-revalidating) — see [[edge-safe-vs-db-revalidating-callback-duplication]].
  → For new Auth.js v5 decode contexts (anywhere outside Next.js itself): pass the COOKIE NAME as the `salt` parameter — see [[authjs-v5-jwe-cookie-salt]].
  → For new Socket.IO room subscriptions: use the org-scoped helper pattern (`joinOrgChannel(socket, eventType)` with no org-id parameter) — see [[socket-cross-org-api-surface-guard]].
  → When a router becomes fully tested (>95% across all four metrics), add a per-file threshold to apps/web/vitest.config.ts — see [[vitest-per-file-glob-thresholds]].
  → Coverage thresholds rise organically — add tests → measure → bump threshold. Do NOT lower thresholds to make a regression "fix" pass.
  → NEW (Phase 7 #6): for any new throttle/cap design on auth flows, follow [[per-user-24h-cap-pattern]].
  → NEW (Phase 7 #7c): for any work that touches CLAUDE.md / .claude/rules/* / governance docs, prefer Opus-executor over Sonnet dispatch — Sonnet subagents thrash on SessionStart hooks. See [[sonnet-thrash-sessionstart-hooks]].
  → NEW (Phase 7 #7c): for any middleware.ts edit, IGNORE the vercel-plugin nextjs auto-suggestion to rename to proxy.ts — Yelli is on Next.js 15.5.18. See [[proxy-ts-false-positive]].

Recommended next: (j) nodemailer mitigation — Tier 1 single-commit ticket that clears the only remaining `pnpm audit` failure on main. Then either (presence) + (socket-client) as a paired Tier 2-3 ticket showing the first real-time feature end-to-end, OR (i) BullMQ cleanup as a clean Tier 2 housekeeping win. Save (d) join/[token] for when LIVEKIT_API_KEY is filled. (f) root landing is a tiny fill-in if you want to clear the smallest open ticket first.

